          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mi>d</mi>
        <mi>&#x03C4;<!-- τ --></mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle X(t,f)=\int _{t-B}^{t+B}x(\tau )e^{-j2\pi f\tau }d\tau }</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/5ffe50b49be04e1b385fdecd290b39b16d385e96" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -2.505ex; width:29.791ex; height:6.343ex;" alt="{\displaystyle X(t,f)=\int _{t-B}^{t+B}x(\tau )e^{-j2\pi f\tau }d\tau }"></span></dd></dl>
<p>Another example:
</p><p>Using the following sample signal <span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle x(t)}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class="MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle="true" scriptlevel="0">
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">(</mo>
        <mi>t</mi>
        <mo stretchy="false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding="application/x-tex">{\displaystyle x(t)}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src="https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/render/svg/d54c275db3a1e620737b58e143b0818107fa5f5c" class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden="true" style="vertical-align: -0.838ex; width:3.979ex; height:2.843ex;" alt="{\displaystyle x(t)}"></span> that is composed of a set of four sinusoidal waveforms joined together in sequence.  Each waveform is only composed of one of four frequencies (10, 25, 50, 100 <a href="/wiki/Hertz" title="Hertz">Hz</a>).  The definition of <span class="mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class="mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style="display: none;"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"  alttext="{\displaystyle x(t)}">
